animal.description:
Mango is a small Staffordshire terrier/pit bull mix.  Per our wonderful dog volunteers, Mango is quiet, calm and a pleasure to walk.  She also does not appear to shed.  She loves car rides and is well behaved in the car. Once Mango falls in love with her human, she is 110% loyal. 

She is housetrained, spayed, current on vaccinations, microchipped, and wormed.

If you are interested in adopting Mango, please call 803-279-1613 or email us at ARKeepers@gmail.com to come meet her.

Thank you for viewing our rescues!

animal.description:
Hello Everyone,

I'm good boy Trevor, and I am needing a good home.  I get along well with other dogs, and I love people.  I am pretty much house trained also.  I love to go fun places and see new things.  I am well socialized and always enjoy a new adventure.  I also like to just curl up on the couch, eat popcorn and watch TV.  

The nice ladies at Ahimsa Rescue where I am staying tell me that I am quite a handsome one and start singing hunk-a-hunk of burning love and something about Elvis Presley....whatever that means.  Anyway, I always try to be a good dog, and I promise I would try extra hard if you would give me a chance.  

If you need a good dog like me please come see me soon.

Love,
Trevor

approx. DOB: January 2016

IMPORTANT:  If you are interested in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue, an on-line adoption form is required. Ahimsa's pets live at private homes in foster care.   Once an application is received an approved a convenient time is set to meet and adopt the pet.  Please complete the on line adoption application at:  www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org to begin the adoption process. 
 
Ahimsa Rescue Foundation is an all volunteer, foster-based rescue in Muldrow, OK. Our pets will be fully vaccinated, spayed or neutered, and microchipped before the adoption becomes final. Adult dogs are heart worm negative and on preventative.  To start the process please visit our website and fill out the adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org

animal.description:
G.L.M.R.....THROWING A LIFE LINE TO MASTIFFS IN NEED

The sweet face on this little girl hides a very sad past. Della has been through a lot in her 2 years, she was seized by the police from outdoor living conditions where she was starving. She also suffers from intense fear of almost everything including humans. She is submissive to the extreme and we hope with time she might recover enough to be adoptable. She is receiving medical treatment from a team of wonderful veterinarians including a behavior specialist and is on a long-term medical hold.  Please consider helping sponsor Della’s medical care.

I am a purebred English Mastiff that was lucky enough to be taken in by the folks at Great Lakes Mastiff Rescue, Inc.  I need a loving, forever home.  If you can give me that home, please visit www.glmr.org to complete an adoption application and a volunteer will contact you soon. PLEASE READ THE FOLLOWING:  GLMR ONLY ADOPTS TO THE GREAT LAKES STATES (MI, OH, IN, IL, WI). PHONE CALLS OR EMAILS WILL NOT BE RETURNED UNLESS YOU HAVE FILLED OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION FIRST. A GLMR REPRESENTATIVE WILL CONTACT YOU WITHIN 2 WEEKS AFTER FILLING OUT A FAMILY PROFILE.

If you are not able to adopt, please consider making a donation to GLMR to help with medical bills for one of these gentle giants. Giant breed dogs also come with giant vet bills. All GLMR dogs are fixed, up to date on shots and healthy when they go to their new homes, but they don't always come to us that way. GLMR does not turn away dogs for health problems! So please help us to help them and make a tax deductible donation to GLMR by clicking the SPONSOR ME button above. Thank you in advance!

animal.description:
Meet Simba, named after the character in the Disney movie The Lion King.  Simba means powerful warrior, and his name certainly suits him.  Simba was pulled from a high kill shelter in North Carolina on his very last day.  Simba came to us emaciated and covered with horrible scars and bite wounds.  Everywhere on his poor, frail body had either scabs, open wounds or scars.  We estimate Simba to be around five years old and he is a bully breed mix.  He is a big eater, but does not show any food aggression or guarding at all, which is amazing considering he was nearly starved to death.  Simba would benefit from some training, as he was never taught leash manners.  Simba has a wonderful personality - he is very energetic and LOVES toys.  He loves to carry his blanket around and play with it.  He will play with basically anything he can find.  Simba loves people and will sit still and soak up all the love and attention you are willing to give him.  Simba is wonderful with people and children and does well with cats, but he needs to be the only dog.  We can only imagine what horrors he endured before he came into our rescue and sadly those encounters caused him to not get along with other dogs.  We don't blame Simba one bit and we totally understand - now we are hoping to find a wonderful adopter who also understands and wants to give Simba the loving home that he so deserves.  We promise that Simba will more than make up for that one short-coming with endless amounts of love, loyalty and companionship.

Simba is house and crate-trained, up to date on all shots, heartworm negative and on heartworm, flea and tick prevention.  Simba clearly had a really rough past and although his body will always bear plenty of scars, he did not let his past form his personality.  "Scars remind us of where we have been, but they do not have to dictate where we are going.”  And this is certainly true for Simba.  Please consider opening your heart and home to this sweet boy and finding out for yourself what an amazing boy he is – you won’t regret it!

animal.description:
3.5yr old. American Bully/American Staffordshire Terrier mix. Friendly girl to those she knows. Enjoys playing and loves the outdoors. Rambunctious at times so she needs a fenced yard for play time. Loyal to her owner(s). Protective of her home. Best as an only dog but does ok with other dogs her size. She is still young so some training would be a big plus and is recommended. Seems fine around younger kids (she used to live with one) but hasn't had much contact with them in a while. She is manageable around cats...but would do best in a home without them.  Her new home should be 1 or 2 adults. Maybe 1 dog (but not necessary, and a fenced yard). Her adopter should make sure that her breed is accepted where she will live and will continue to have her should a move happen. Training (obedience and/or behavioral) is something that we recommend setting up or continuing (if she has already started sessions).
Available to a good experienced home, only! DOB 12/15/16 

Fee is $75




















OLD INFO:

11mo. old American Bully. Parents are registered champions. Friendly girl but very rambunctious. Fine with kids (older are best). Fine with other dogs but would probably do best as the only dog since she doesn't always like sharing her food, treats,  and toys.
She did not come from the best situation and home so she needs some love and basic training. An owner experienced in bully breeds is best!


Fee is $125
















OLD INFO:

This puppy is an AMERICAN BULLY (a recently formed companion breed dog). 8 weeks old. Owner surrender. Parents of the pup are champion registered and blue bloods (not sure what that means exactly) and are beautiful. This pup and sibling are looking for homes...permanent homes (does not have to go together). Must be experienced with bully breeds and preferably own your own home w/a fenced yard (due to the rising problem with bully breeds being allowed in certain apartments, etc.). Be sure to check with your HOA.
Will be a beautiful strong puppy that will be a great family dog, also.
(PICTURES COMING SOON!)


Fee is 300 (includes shots, spay when cleared by vet, and microchip)


Info On The Breed:

Please EMAIL apassionforpaws@gmail.com and wait for confirmation of your appointment before coming to visit the Akita Ranch. We also request that visitors wear masks. 107 lbs - needs a breed savvy ownerFalcor will wait as long as it takes for you to come and get him. He is a loving, devoted companion with adorable puppy-like play behavior. He LOVES chasing his big red ball and is always up for a game of fetch or a walk! Falcor is not a high energy dog but he does need a large, secure yard with room to run or an active owner who will walk him daily. NO CHILDREN UNDER 18. He has not lived with other animals and it would be up to his new owner to introduce him slowly and carefully integrate him into a home with other pets or be willing to keep the animals safely separated. Falcor is ridiculously good-looking but beyond his handsome good looks, he is loyal, brave, intelligent and possesses all the lovable Akita traits!
Come meet handsome Falcor at Akita Ranch 28930 Ellis Ave, Romoland, CA (open 10-5, 7 days) or email: apassionforpaws@gmail.com for adoption information.

animal.description:
Tucker will be staying with his foster family

We have had no sincere and suited enquiries

He requires a fenced yard (not invisible fence) and experience with a flight risk dog so he is safest to stay where he knows


WHY WAS THIS DOG IN NEED??- Sadly this dog has a history of being failed by at least 3 previous owners . 2nd owners found him as a stray/dumped in the country and took him in - then surrendered to vet. 
He then was adopted out to his most recent owner. 
We were asked to help this emaciated (on intake) fellow-that was was thought to be a wandering stray. 
Then the owner was found that had taken him in only a few weeks before. 
It does not appear that he even had his own share of food, with his packmates in the outdoor shed he was living in.
He was left to wander looking for food, safety.. and maybe his very 1st family ?? His last owner allowed rescue to secure him and surrendered to rescue so he could find a better home.

WHERE IS THIS DOG NOW ?- He is now in foster care in Goderich. He lives with adults and is used to living with other dogs.

**ALL ABOUT TUCKER  
Tucker is fully vetted
He is a wonderful passenger in the vehicle (albeit scared to get in initially) and a fantastic dog in general.
He was guessed to be about 6-7 yrs old on intake so could be 9-10 now as he arrive January 2017.

Tucker had  1 lump removed off muzzle with chemotherapy in June and 4 lump removed in July 2020 and they are all benign.

Peppy is in a forever foster home due to serious, ongoing health issues. His foster parents have opened their hearts and home to dear Peppy. We know that it would be too stressful for Peppy to transition to a new home at this point. His foster parents donate their time to caring for Peppy, but caring for him requires more than love. Our rescue provides nutritious food, medications and vital veterinary care.

Adopt A Dog/Save A Life relies on the generosity of donors to cover the cost of medication and procedures required to keep dogs like Peppy comfortable during their remaining days. If you would like make a donation in support of Peppy's care, please let us know!

Peppy is one of the sweetest dogs you will ever meet! He is 12 years old and weighs approximately 12 pounds. He originally came to us with another little Pomeranian. He and Layla were very bonded. Layla also had very serious health issues and she recently passed away due to her heart condition. We did all we could to keep her comfortable until her passing. They were both surrendered to us because their owner was moving and not able to take them along or care for them properly. They did get adopted but were returned. As mentioned, both Layla and Peppy had several health issues when we first rescued them. Thanks to the support of our donors we were able to get them the medical care they required and we are now able to keep Peppy comfortable and happy in his forever foster home.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ: Thank you for your interest in one of our adoptable dogs!  All dogs listed are still available.  If interested, please complete our no obligation application.  This can be found at www.waldosmuttleycrew.org.  Select the Applications tab, then Adoption Application. THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS.  It can take up to a week to process an application.  We are an all-volunteer rescue so please be patient.

Our adoption area is limited to a 4 hour radius of Indianapolis.  We try our best to provide all information in our bios.  If you have any specific questions, feel free to ask during the interview process.  Some of our dogs have special requirements such as needs another dog in the home or requires a physical and permanent fenced yard.  These requirements are not negotiable.  Unless otherwise noted, we do not cat test our adoptable dogs.  We also require that all pets in your household be spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and on a monthly heartworm/flea preventative. 

E-MAILS: We do not respond to e-mail inquiries without an application.  We regret that we cannot respond to every e-mail unless you fill out an application.  

All the dogs we offer for adoption have been spayed/neutered, wormed and microchipped, are up-to-date on immunizations, have been tested for heartworm and are currently receiving a monthly preventative.  If the dog had additional medical issues, those have also been addressed.  Visit our website www.waldosmuttleycrew.org for more information and to complete an application.

Fallon is a gorgeous 4 year old Great Pyrenees/husky mix who weighs a 
lean 65-70 lbs.  She's lithe & athletic and simply beautiful!  We are 
very proud of her as when we got her, Fallon was terrified of all men 
and anxious with strangers; she's come from a very abusive home.  With 
time & gentleness, she has learned that people aren't going to hurt her 
anymore.  Given a few minutes to warm up and a treat or two, Fallon 
leans into people for ear scratches, her tail waving gently as she 
enjoys the attention.  She's very gentle when getting pet and takes 
treats so softly.  Fallon is so loyal to the people she knows; her 
devotion is amazing.  Because she's an active girl who's favorite 
activities involve high speed chases & games of tug of war, Fallon needs 
to go to a home with a large, playful dog who also enjoys these 
activities.  We can't imagine her without a doggy companion; she just 
wouldn't be complete.  Fallon is good with most other dogs but she's 
drawn to large males ... with her looks, they do seem to find her 
irresistible as well.  She will need a physical fence in her new home so 
that she has room to run & play.  Fallon's adoption fee is $175; she's 
spayed, microchipped and current on vaccinations as well monthly 
heartworm/flea preventative.

animal.description:
April’s journey with Adopt-A-Dog began in October of 2015. She came from the Ross County Humane Society in Ohio, and as she settled in we saw how fearful April was and that she would need a lot of confidence-building in order to make her more comfortable in both a home and the outside world. Despite that, we were able to get April adopted within the month, with her family immediately beginning training with us we thought April landed in the right home. After a few months, the family contacted us and decided April was not the right fit for them. During her first couple of weeks back with us, we noticed some behavioral changes in April, including a more reserved and uneasy nature when it came to meeting strangers. Our main goal was to build her trust and confidence around people and once over that hurdle, we realized how desperately this gorgeous girl wanted to please her people. 

Coming back into our shelter was not the ideal environment for April’s health, so we knew right away that we had to get her a friend. We matched her with Sora and now the best part of April’s day is getting out in the yard with her best friend. This confidence boost of being around another dog led April to be placed in foster with one of our staff members. In that home, she was with three other dogs and we were able to really understand her hesitation with people. As her fosters gained her trust, April built more confidence knowing that they would not hurt her.  

For April’s adoption, her new family would have to meet her several times and come to learn the excellent training she has learned here at Adopt-A-Dog. Along with her fear-based behavior, April does resource guard from other dogs and humans. Our trainer and Behavior Coordinator would equip any family with the training they need and we would follow up with training after adoption to ensure April and her new family’s success.

 An ideal home for April would be one with owners who understand and have experience with fearful dogs and can help build a trusting and lasting relationship with her. We know that this home is out there and April cannot wait to find it!


Contact the Adoptions team at (914) 273-1674 or adoptions@adoptadog,org for more information!

The first step to adopting one of our dogs is to fill out our online adoptions questionnaire located here: https://forms.gle/5heEH8S6c7zXBneD7

animal.description:
TRUE BEAGLE LOVER NEEDED! 

Snap was surrendered to us by his owner, and has been with us for TOO LONG! 
Snap is now 5 years old, is adorable, active, playful, social, good with other dogs, and just wants someone to love him. 

Snap does have separation anxiety, which is well controlled with medication (which will need to be maintained post-adoption). This sounds weird, but he seriously needs a home with a window he can look out during the day...it seems to help his separation anxiety if he can do so. Adopters experienced with separation anxiety are preferred since it will likely temporarily worsen when he is placed in a new home.  Someone who works part-time or does not have a standard "9-5 + commute" type of time away from the home would be best, and he needs another friendly dog in the home for sure. 

Snap is a typical high energy young beagle, and will bolt out doors, so a fenced in yard is recommended. He loves other dogs, but has times of chasing the cats so we do not recommend a home with cats. Snap CANNOT be crated, so this cannot be a consideration for him. He is housetrained. Any accidents that occur are related to anxiety or being left for too long. Snap loves to snuggle, and gets very attached to people very quickly. Someone willing to take him for walks and give him adequate exercise would be awesome. We are recommending against children in the home given that Snap is very excitable, howls loudly when excited, and will likely jump up on and scare young children. (The howling would likely rule out apartment dwellers and/or those concerned with noise issues.) Snap does have a bite history due to 2 occurrences (over 8 months) towards the same person in one of our foster homes. No incidents have occurred in other environments, but Snap can be "mouthy" when excited and when playing which is also why we will not consider an adoptive home for him with children in it.  

Snap is incredibly responsive to positive reinforcement training. Someone willing to continue his training, and even pursue additional training would be his ideal adopter! We can and will share additional information about Snap through our adoption process, so if interested, please review our adoption process, requirements and submit an application here: www.beaglerescueleague.org/adoption

There is helpful info on our website: huskyhavenofla.org- BUT it is outdated with some info We do not have funds to complete  a new website
The adopt fee stated is VERY old: Our current adopt fee for adults is bet $245 and $285 
Everything is done: all vaccines/spay o r neuter/microchip/evaluation. If vet intervention was needed, this info will be provided as well 
PLUS 30 dys FREE vet insurance and access to continue vet insurance at VERY low cost 
Most dogs have videos and "clicking" on the video link ( the little film icon) is helpful to learn more.. 

PLS DO NOT submit an application if you are NOT ready to adopt within the next 2 wks. 

If any of the following LIST applies to you pls EMAIL first BEFORE applying so we can give you addl info:

If you have a sml dog weighing less than 35 lbs
If you have a cat or cats
If your current fencing is NOT min 6 foot all the way around including the gates
(Some of the dogs are ok with 5 foot but NOTHING less)
If you have an inground swimming pool NOT safely fenced off 
If the location you are residing at is your parents home
If you are a renter, we REQUIRE WRITTEN landlord approval
PLS make sure you have asked if there are restrictions re the breed or size or weight for your complex.

animal.description:
Please read Tyler’s description carefully and ONLY inquire if you meet the requirements below.

Tyler must be the only pet in the home. Tyler needs a tall wood privacy fence, no short chain link fences 4 ft tall. No children in the home, if kids visit, it must not be often as Tyler is not used to kids and was previously abused and has trust issues. 

Tyler is a beautiful dog, but PLEASE don’t inquire because he’s handsome. He needs a person with extensive dog experience, someone who’s raised multiple dogs over the years please. Tyler does best with women and has only lived with women. He’s met 2 men ever that he trusted. He will not be adopted to a home with men alone, there needs to be a woman in his home.
Tyler is a darling boy but a very special dog with specific needs. 

Please read below and only inquire if you meet his requirements below and are serious about helping a dog with special needs and behavior issues.

Tyler is a 6 year old, male,  Terrier/Poodle mix, and weighs around 30 lbs. He's a gorgeous boy and is very loving once he gets to know and trust you. Tyler needs extra time to get used to new people and will do best after a few introductions. He was very scared when we first got him and he didn't trust anyone. A trainer said he was previously abused which makes sense why it takes time for him to become comfortable with new people.

He loves our volunteers, who he knows and trusts. He needs a calm, loving person and home, and someone with a lot of dog experience. He doesn't like strangers coming up to him until he gets to know them well. He must have the right adopter and right home for this to work out. He will do best in a very calm, quiet home with someone who will be patient until he comes out of his shell. An apartment will not work. Not a home with much company or out of town visitors either. Preferably a one or two person home with no children or grandchildren. Tyler is not good with small kids at all.

If someone will give him a chance, they will be very happy they did. He’s one of the most loving dogs ever and even likes to give hugs around your neck!
Tyler loves to play with toys and to go for walks and especially likes to hang out on the sofa. He rides great in the car also. He must be the only pet in the home. Other animals who get too close really seems to bother him. He has never been around children and given that he's nervous with new people at first, kids will not be suitable for him. The most important thing is a calm, quiet home with one or two people, preferably someone a little older and more settled. Young adults, out of college, engaged or who will have children in the future won't be the right match for Tyler. He’s still very active so we’d like someone in the 40-60 year old age range.

In order for Tyler to get used to someone new, it will take several introductions. 
We've had dogs like Tyler in the past and when we take things slow, they work out beautifully for the dog and for the adopter.

Only local adopters/Metro Atlanta only - No Exceptions

animal.description:
IF THIS LISTING IS STILL UP, they are still available for adoption!    Inquiries asking about availability will not be answered. E-mails or contact forms that are submitted prior to completing an adoption application will not be answered.

***Please read this first, as it answers the majority of questions we receive***

Please do not contact us about specific dogs until you have completed our Adoption Application FIRST --- located at www.aussierescue.org

Once we receive your application, we will contact you. This chapter only receives applications from applicants living in Texas and Oklahoma. If you live outside of TX or OK, you will need to contact our organizations Management Team first: managementteam2@yahoo.com). Out-of-state adoptions are considered on a case-by-case basis.

Our organization requires prospective adopters to complete an approval process prior to meeting with dogs in our program. This includes:

*Completion of Adoption Application
*Veterinarian Check
*Reference Checks (non-relatives)
*Home Visit

Our ultimate goal is to screen and counsel potential homes to the best of our ability in an effort to find the most perfect match and fit for their lifestyle.

Please keep in mind that color and appearance of the available dog is last on our priority list, and will have no bearing on adoption placement decisions.

Please refrain from contacting members of our organization or asking about specific dogs/potential matches until after your screening process has been completed and approved. 

***Our organization requires a donation of $300 to adopt.***
--------------------------------------------------------

ABOUT KIITOS:
Rep:  Kim Griswold / kimgriswold@att.net

Kiitos is located in Dallas, TX and it is required that you travel there to meet him in person to adopt, no exceptions.  We do need the entire party to be involved when meeting available dogs, including every family member and dog(s) that currently live in your home.  

This handsome boy is a low energy dog who loves every person he meets.  He loves going for his daily walk, and walks beautiful on a leash.  His favorite past-time is getting to smell all the smells and greet everyone he passes.  He is a calm and easy going dog that is happy to spend time inside with his person, looking lovingly into your eyes.  He is housebroken and crate trained, but is also trustworthy in the house uncrated.  He rides well in the car and actually rather enjoys road trips.  

Some of you may remember him back when we first rescued him from a shelter in 2016 with a large, 2# tumor attached to his paw. After having that surgically removed and assessed at Texas A&M (benign growth), he then went through heartworm treatment and later found a home in early 2017.

However, his story unfortunately didn't stop there. 4 months after he was adopted, his single mom experienced a terrible car wreck and was rushed to intensive care, temporarily going into a coma. Fortunately, a thoughtful neighbor knew about the situation and went over, every day, to take care of Kiitos, who was stranded alone at his house. We only became aware of the situation when the neighbor decided to call us from the info on his ARPH ID tag. We quickly went and picked him up and kept him in temporary foster care until his mom was able to be released from the hospital several weeks later... at which point, they were reunited.

Sadly, in the spring of 2018, we began receiving repeated calls from good samaritans that Kiitos was running loose... and despite every attempt to continue making it work, his adopter was no longer able to physically care for him and he was returned.

So... after all this... Kiitos is now, once again, searching for his final and permanent home.  

He is now approximately 10 yrs old, and keeps getting passed over due to his age.   We just hope that he can FINALLY find some stability in his life.  He is so full of love and affection that he would prefer to have all the attention to himself as an only dog, but we will consider a home with other dogs on an individual basis.  Originally, he was not a fan of felines, but over time, he has proven trustworthy with any indoor cat that is dog-savvy.
animal.name: ARPH #13584 - Kiitos

animal.description:
Jinx is a 5 year old border collie looking for a home where he can stay busy and challanged. He is smart, intense and has a high drive. We think he could excel at agility or obedience and likely other dog sports! He hasn’t been trained to herd but shows herding instinct. 

We’ve fostered many border collies and other heeding breeds. He is more high drive than your typical border. He needs an experienced owner with an interest in training or dog sports. He would not do well living in an apartment or without a yard. 

He is a very sweet boy who loves to snuggle as much as play! He is very loyal and wants to please his people.  He is housebroken and crate trained. This boy loves to play fetch as well as the weirdest way of pushing balls around the yard with his face! 

Jinx has lived with many dogs and does well with most, but can be selective. To be cautious, he should not go to a home with small dogs. He is not a good candidate for going to dog parks. He is not good with cats. 

Jinx is neutered,  vaccinated, heartworm negative, and microchipped. 

He is not right for everyone, but he will be an amazing friend to the right family!

*Jinx is a courtesy post,  please do not contact MUSHR but instead email his foster owner at megwagner@hotmail.com and include some information about your family. Jinx is fostered outside of the metro area, you must be willing to travel to meet him.*

Due to the high level of interest in dog adoptions due to quarantine I’m having trouble keeping up on inquiries. Emails will only be returned to perspective adopters who have read his bio and understand his needs.

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE - THE PUPPIES/DOGS IN THESE PHOTOS ARE NOT ADOPTABLE; THEY ARE MEANT TO SHOW THE VARIETY OF RESCUE PUPS IN OUR ORGANIZATION

Helping Paws Me is searching for quality foster homes in the greater PORTLAND, MAINE area.  Our foster families need to be within 1-hour driving distance of our Vet in case the foster puppy needs to be seen while in foster care.  We are unable to approve foster homes more than 1-hour from Portland at this time, but encourage you to reach out to your local animal shelter to inquire about foster opportunities.

We work with rescue groups in the Magee, Mississippi area to rescue unwanted shelter puppies & dogs and find them loving homes in New England.  Since we do not have a physical shelter, our network of foster families commit to taking a rescue puppy or dog into their home and give him or her love, care and attention.  The average foster period is a week, but can be longer.

Why foster?

Fostering a dog is one of the most rewarding experiences you can have.  By taking a dog in need temporarily into your home you are:
•freeing up a spot so our rescue group can take in another dog.
•giving your foster dog the time he needs to be ready for adoption.
•helping our rescue group learn more about the dog so he can end up in the best home possible.
•socializing the dog to a home environment and possibly getting him used to being around other pets and different types of people.

If you are interested in learning more about fostering, please e-mail our volunteers at helpingpawsme@gmail.com.  We do require all potential foster homes to complete our foster application which can be found at: helpingpawsme.org

animal.description:
PLEASE  PLEASE READ CAREFULLY.  Most of your questions will be answered in this Biography.

*House Trained
*Crate Trained
*Loves Kids
*Loves to Play
*Would do Best as an Only Dog
*Doesn't Well With Cats

ZEE ZEE lives to be loved and she's not afraid to show it. Just check out those expressive eyebrows! She likes to play with her toys, chew on her bones, go for walks and snuggle on the couch. Her favorite game is playing fetch, hands down. Ball = Life for ZeeZee.

Her spirit is so loving, and she just wants to soak up what life has to offer, all with the cutest tongue out smile on her face. Zee Zee loves children most of all. She wants to be part of an active home and in the middle of a loving family dynamic. She is crate trained, and potty trained. Though, she isn’t fond of going out in the rain, like many other pups out there.

Zee Zee would do best as an only dog and doesn’t prefer the company of other dogs, especially in close quarters. She does well with cats, so long as she has guidance on how to behave.

She is very much a people oriented dog, and never forgets her favorite humans. She regularly goes to daycare with her foster mom, where she gets showered with love and attention from the staff. She always waits patiently and calmly for a snack, and watches for the signal ahead before she eats her meals.

An ideal candidate for her adoption would be an adopter that is dog savvy, patient, active, kind and dedicated to continuing her personal growth. Her foster mom is a dog trainer who has spent a lot of time teaching Zee basic obedience and leash walking skills. Continuing her work is essential. (Her foster mom is happy to help out in that department, too!)

ZeeZee is a Boxer mix with an estimated date of birth of 1/6/2016. She is also vaccinated, microchipped and spayed.

For more information on our adoption process, please visit our website at www.youluckydogrescue.org and read our Adoption FAQ's and Before You Adopt documents. In addition you can complete an online adoption application from our website. You can also email info@youluckydogrescue.org for additional details.

Our adoption fee is $300 and includes all age appropriate vaccines, spay or neuter and microchipping. All YLDR dogs are provided monthly heart worm & flea preventatives and heart worm tested annually beginning at the age of 12 weeks.

The breed and age included in this listing is based upon the opinion of a vet that has examined the dog. We cannot confirm the age of the dog unless the dog was born in the care of the rescue. 

We are located in the metro Atlanta area. We currently do not allow out of state adoptions as a home check is required as part of the adoption process.

ADOPTION APPLICATION:  youluckydogrescue.org

Age:	12 years
Gender:	Male
Color:	Black & White
Weight:	50 lbs
Variety:	Mix
Tam is a sweet old man who came to ESRA from a hoarding situation in October of 2016. 

When he arrived in his foster home, he was too scared to come out from under the kitchen table to socialize with his foster mom and foster sisters. 
But after a few days, he warmed up to them and blossomed into a fine gentleman. He was housetrained after only two accidents, so you can definitely teach an old dog new tricks, especially when they are as smart as this old man. 

The veterinarian estimated Tam to be about 12 years old, but don't let his age fool you. He keeps up with his young foster sisters on the dog park trails and insists on jumping onto the porch instead of taking the stairs. His recent health check and blood work shows that he is very healthy for his age. He is blind in his left eye, but you would never know it. He is good around other dogs, cats, and children, and he loves to follow his foster mom everywhere she goes. He is an extremely sweet boy that deserves a good retirement home and a family to call his own. 

Tam is fully vaccinated, neutered and ready to go home!
Please read the Adoption FAQ and get an Adoption Application approved before inquiring about Tam.

animal.description:
This is the story of Pogo:

In May of 2015, Pogo was thrown out a car window in front of our Lowe's store. Tossed out like a piece of trash!
 Thank God we were able to catch him.
 I took him home. Pogo was infested with fleas and was starving.
 It took me many months just for him to trust me. Pogo is still a bit shy of men.
 On May 3rd of 2016 I was able to get him neutered. This is when I found out he was heart worm positive. The vet I used was
 Clay Humane in  Orange Park. At that time they estimated him to be under two years old.
 Pogo is cat friendly. Pogo is not sure if he likes other dogs or not. I have kept him away from dogs because he gets nervous and cries. He could be dog aggressive but I have yet to find out.
 Pogo has been around other people, but not much. I am not sure if he likes children as I have not socialized him.
 Pogo is being treated for heartworms now.

animal.description:
Sieva is a 61 lb female shepherd/lab mix with a snaggle tooth, floppy ears and a coat that’s soft and fuzzy. She was surrendered to the rescue alongside her puppies who have since been adopted. 

We don’t know much about her history but could take a guess that she had a rough start in life. She had heartworms when she first came to us, which have since been treated fully, and a tail that looks like it may have been poorly cropped ¾ of the way down.

She’s a smart gal, who loves to learn new training tricks, play with a ball, and snuggle up next to you while you watch TV. She aims to please and is learning something new every single day. 

Because of her rough start, Sieva has needed some time to go through behavioral rehabilitation, and learn how to be a dog again. She still struggles with other animals, and would do best in a home without other animals or children present. 

Her ideal adopter would be someone who is patient, loving, kind and would continue her training. Structure, and routine help her thrive, and be the happy go lucky dog that she wants to be.

For more information on our adoption process, please visit our website at www.youluckydogrescue.org and read our Adoption FAQ's and Before You Adopt documents. In addition you can complete an online adoption application from our website. You can also email info@youluckydogrescue.org for additional details.  

Our adoption fee is $300 and includes all age appropriate vaccines, spay  or neuter and microchipping.  The breed and age included in this listing is based upon the opinion of a vet that has examined the dog.  We cannot confirm the age of the dog unless the dog was born in the care of the rescue.  We are located in the metro Atlanta area.   We currently do not allow out of state adoptions as a home check is required as part of the adoption process.

animal.description:
THE DOGS IN PHOTO(s) ARE NOT AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION

https://caninehumane.org/how-to-help/foster/

Do you want to care for another dog? Are you home during the day? 
Canine Humane Network is looking for foster homes for its rescue dogs.


Fostering a dog is one of the most rewarding experiences you can have.

By taking a homeless dog temporarily into your home you are giving your foster dog the time he needs to be ready for adoption and saving him from terrible conditions or in many cases, euthanasia. In addition, you are helping us learn more about the dog so he can end up in the best possible permanent home. Lastly, you are socializing the dog to a home environment and providing him with love and attention, helping your foster dog to grow in confidence and become a happy, well-adjusted pet!
 
So what exactly does fostering entail? 
 
When you become a foster, you agree to take a homeless dog into your home and provide care, love, and shelter while the adoption team finds a perfect forever home for your visitor. CHN provides you with all of the food, supplies, and support you need; all you need is a passion for helping dogs in need! 
 
If you are interested in fostering a dog in need, please click the link below and fill out a new foster application! We can’t wait for you to become part of our team!

https://caninehumane.org/how-to-help/foster/

animal.description:
Born Oct. 2011, Maddie is our little Miss Cutie Patootie! She is a short and stocky malamute girl with so much personality. She is guaranteed to make you smile every day.  Maddie has a flirtatious personality but she needs to develop trust before you may reciprocate affection. She is called a little miss spitfire because she is a tough independent little cookie full of sass. She loves her crate where she feels safe & hanging outside supervising everyone and everything. She likes hiking too.

Maddie is happy laying around on her doggy bed and being in the same room as you. Don't let that adorable teddy bear look fool you, she isn't a cuddler and prefers her space. She will give you a show with high fives, and becomes full of excitement for treat time! Just give her space and time to get to know you. 

She had a very rough life and is hesitant to trust people. Despite this, she sits nicely to put her collar on before going on a walk. She also rides well in the car but generally speaking, Maddie doesn't just do things willingly, which is why force-free training works. She likes to protest a little bit just enough so she feels like she had a choice.  

She does not like other dogs but can be around them. If given the chance she will let other dogs know she is boss and that's why we recommend her as being the only dog in the home. When you are out on a walk she won't get upset seeing another dog as long as they are behaving. She isn't dog aggressive but won't back down from a challenge either. 

Maddie was debarked as a pup so she doesn't have her 'woo-woo' but don't let that stop you from giving this girl her second chance. She needs a home with Northern Breed & force-free dog training experience. She has a strict limited ingredient diet --- salmon only protein and fat. She loves KronchUSA salmon treats & cold pressed salmon oil. Typical malamute she cannot be around small dogs or pets including cats. 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering this dog, please contact CHAAMP at CHAAMPapplication@gmail.com for an application. You may also complete an application online thru our web site, www.CHAAMP.org

CHAAMP accepts applications ONLY from Maryland, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Virginia, West Virginia, and Washington DC. The information on your application will help CHAAMP determine which of our dogs is a good match for you and your family, based upon your lifestyle, other pets, etc. A home visit is required prior to all adoptions. Many of our dogs are fostered in private homes and cannot be visited until you have been approved for adoption. 

ADOPTION FEES
~Older dogs (eight years old or over) the adoption fee is $100.00 

All dogs are micro chipped, spayed and neutered and up to date on vaccines. These fees help us cover these costs.  The rates are higher for puppies because they require more visits to the vet and shots. 

CHAAMP IS NOT A SHELTER. We are volunteers over a 7-state area dedicated to helping Malamutes in our rescue area. You can read more about Malamutes and about CHAAMP by visiting www.CHAAMP.org

animal.description: Reyna is a beautiful Shepherd/Doberman mix who was born in August 2016. She weighs about 50 lbs.  Reyna survived parvo as a puppy but unfortunately, was subsequently diagnosed with two other congenital issues - Megaesophagus (ME) and Exocrine Pancreatic Insufficiency (EPI).  Dogs with ME have a dilated esophagus due to lack of muscle tone, which causes food to sit in the esophagus rather than travel to the stomach. Reyna's ME is very mild and is managed by making sure she eats and drinks from an elevated feeder. EPI occurs when the pancreas does not secrete the enzymes needed to digest food and results in weight loss and diarrhea.  Reyna's EPI is managed by adding a supplement to her food that costs approximately $100 per month.  Both conditions are currently well-managed.  Reyna is good with most of the dogs in her foster home but can be pushy sometimes.  She likes to chase cats.  Reyna does not meet new dogs well – she becomes very defensive, so needs time to make new dog friends.  She is good with people but too active for small children.  She is housebroken and crate trained.  Reyna would love to have a family of her own.

animal.description: TJ is such a great dog. He is approximately 3 yrs. old and loves people.  His excited state when seeing people he knows is to nip them on their fingers to get attention which could be alarming to small children therefore we believe he would do best with older children who would not be startled with this form of affection.  He does know the "sit" command and that helps to calm him down a little.  We believe he is a Staffordshire Terrier mixed with perhaps a boxer. He is currently fostered where he has to stay outside so we don't know if he is house trained.  He does have a large outside chain link kennel he stays in at night which has a designated area for relieving himself and he does use that area so we feel he would be easy to house train.  He isn't a big marker outside so we think that would not be a big issue inside the house but he would need to be watched to correct that issue should it arise.  He gets along with most dogs and has a best friend "Sofie" who he runs and plays with and they are in kennels next to each other.  We believe he would do best with a female dog since we already know he does so well with Sofie who is a girl.  We don't know how he is with cats.  Because our adoption process includes a home visit for a yard check, he is available for adoption in the immediate DFW area only. He is neutered, current on his vaccinations and heartworm tested and micro chipped.  If you are seriously interested in meeting TJ outside our adoption events you may email us for a questionnaire to fill out.  If it looks like your home would be a good match for TJ we can set up a meet and greet.  His adoption fee is $150.

animal.description:
Here's Johnny.....! He is an almost three year old chihuahua. He came in to Animal Control as a surrender after his owner died. He is a bigger Chihuahua weighing at about 12 pounds. Johnny is a tough case.... he is a "bite now, ask questions later" kind of dog. We couldn't even get him out of the kennel at Animal Control. After about 24 hours, he would let us handle him. His foster mom still cannot handle him if he is in his dog bed.... he will growl and bite and fight to the death. He wants to do everything on his own terms. He is hard to handle in terms of Frontlining, clipping nails, etc. He doesn't like to go outside, so he's been going on a potty pad. His foster mom can't always pick him up to take him out (bites). He does take food nicely from her hand and he will also jump up and sleep next to her, as well as let her hold him and pet him on her lap. She can also pick him up, provided she is not doing something he doesn't like (i.e., taking him outside). He gets along okay with the other dogs and he is okay with the cat too. So, his foster mom will keep working on Johnny. He is going to take a patient and loving, quiet home. Because Johnny is set in his ways, a home with small children is out of the question. Whoever adopts him will need to make sure he has his space. If he's in his bed, just leave him alone. AND, if you love WEIRDO dogs, then this dog is for you! He has come out of his shell a bit and will still bite on occasion, but not too often. He loves to play "red light, green light" with his foster mom. He will chase her if she turns around.... then if she faces him, he stops short. He gives weird kisses, but only on his own terms. He loves to get attention when she is sitting. Particularly in the bathroom. But sitting anywhere, he jumps up on her lap. He has a crazy side-eye. But the longer we get to know the little weirdo, he has grown on us. He brings new meaning to weird Chihuahua, that's for sure! Johnny is neutered, current on his vaccinations and micro chipped. His adoption fee is $135. If you would like to apply to adopt Johnny or any of his rescue friends, please visit our website to complete and adoption application by clicking on the link below:

https://form.jotform.com/50308432400137

animal.description:
Sprinkles is a little shy and is initially hesitant when meeting new people and dogs.  She likes other dogs and loves her people.  Once she's comfortable, she wants to snuggle up in your lap and grin at you.  

We guesstimate her birthday in Nov. 2012.  She weighs about 25 lb, so if you want a loving little white pup, sprinkled with color flecks, contact us :)

Sprinkles needs to be an only dog or in a home with bigger dogs.  She enjoys playing with other dogs and playing by herself - especially with squeaky toys.  She's house / leash / crate-trained.  She rides well in a car once she is confident in her handler.  Overall, Sprinkles is a calm, docile dog.

*************
April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Affectionately known as "The Shyles", Shawn (white stripe) and Kyle are a dad and son duo who were surrendered to a local shelter. We rescued senior Shawn and knew we couldn't leave Kyle behind. So we have ourselves a youngster!
We don't know if they were abused or under socialized, or both. Everything appeared to be brand new to them and they needed to learn how to just be dogs. They've made tremendous progress and have really settled in to being a part of the family. 
Shawn is 8 years old and weighs about 14 lbs and Kyle is 2 year old and weighs about 12 lbs. They seem to be a mixture of dachshund, chi, beagle and maybe a splash of min pin. 
They get along with other dogs, though may bark at bigger ones until they get used to them. Cats are too much fun to bother. They are good with gentle teenagers.
The Shyles are a super-bonded pair and they'll need to be adopted together. They will do well in a home where they can move at a pace that's comfortable for them and we recommend an adopter who has experience with timid dogs. Once they settle in and trust, they are big cuddle monsters, love to play and are little mischief makers.

animal.description:
Animal is goofy and playful.  He got his name from the character Animal from the Muppets.  He is always looking for something to do to occupy his mind.   He has been with us almost 4 years and calls our free roam sanctuary home until someone opens their heart and home to this wonderful boy.  He has made friends with multiple dogs and enjoys lounging under the shade trees or curled up on his bed inside. 
He is a loving and very happy dog but suffers without medication to help with anxiety.  Due to a spinal condition that can effects his mobility he takes a joint supplement and anti inflammatory medication.   We love our little Animal and he loves us but we know he deserves the one on one attention he would receive in a home of his own.   A home where he can shine, and grow old with someone who will love him for all of his years.  

Animal is currently spending time at our sanctuary getting much needed one on one time and exercising in the play yards. Are you interested in meeting Animal? Please email traci.care@gmail.com for more information!

All C.A.R.E rescue dogs are fully vaccinated, heartworm tested, spayed/neutered, worm/flea free, and dogs are microchipped! So all you need to provide is the love.

Fill out an adoption application here: http://www.carerescue.org/dog-adoption

Our adoption fee is a minimum $100 tax deductible donation. All donations are used for rescue and  medical care of animals in need.  If you don't have room to take home a pet but want to support our efforts to save animals in need, please consider making a donation. We are not city or state funded and rely solely on private donations that allow us to continue saving lives.

To learn more about us or to give a life saving donation please visit http://www.carerescue.org

animal.description:
Most of the animals listed here are in foster homes, but some are still residing at the Granite City Animal Control until they can be adopted or there is a foster home opening. Pound Pets Inc rescue can always use more fosters.  If you are interested in fostering, the foster application is located here: https://form.jotform.com/50784968756173

Our Adoption Process: 
*You must complete an adoption application before meeting an animal.
*We do all checks on references and vet checks. 
*Please let your references know we will be calling. 
*Once approved, you can set up an appointment to meet any of the animals at the Granite City Animal Control, or the ones in foster homes. 
*There will be a meet and greet and then a home visit.
*After that you will sign an adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. 

$85 for Rabbits / $80 for Cats / $100 Kittens / $150 for Dogs / $200 for Puppies Six Months & Under

The dog adoption application is located here:
https://form.jotform.com/31997643682166

All our animals are completely vetted with the required vaccinations, microchipped and spayed/neutered before leaving the rescue. 
Including: 
Cats will have FIV/FeLV testing
Dogs will have Heartworm testing
Rabbits will have a wellness check 

______________________________________________________________


Many times we also get feral cats or semi-friendly cats (can be petted but doesn't like to be held) needing barn homes. You will need to provide shelter and food. There are not any adoption fees for barn cats (donations are accepted) but you will still need to fill out the cat adoption form. Just list the number of barn cats you are wanting. 

______________________________________________________________

We are a small foster based rescue but some of our animals are residing at the Granite City Animal Control in Madison County, Illinois until they can be adopted, fostered or pulled by another rescue. 

Pound Pets Inc Rescue can always use more fosters.
If you are interested in fostering, the foster application is located here:

https://form.jotform.com/50784968756173

______________________________________________________________

Pound Pets volunteers cleans the animal control building, we are the caregivers for the animals brought in. Once they come through the door, they become our responsibility. We photograph all animals and post to the Pound Pets Facebook page. We provide them clean kennels, beds, blankets, toys, treats, outside play time, walks and human interaction. We try to comfort the scared, keep the high-energy ones exercised and provide plenty of love and affection to make their time at animal control as less stressful as possible. 

Sometimes they get reclaimed by their families and sometimes they don't. If they don't it is our responsibility to find the adopters, fosters or rescues to save them from euthanasia. 

We get in sick and injured animals as well. They do not sit in their kennels or cages needing veterinary care. Once we see the need for care they are taken to the vet. Sometimes the illness or injury is minor and the city will cover the bill, Other times when it's not, we do. We do all of this on our own dime. We buy the food, the beds, the blankets, the toys, and all the other things that go into care for the animals. Sometimes things are donated and that is wonderful!! We pay the medical bills that the city doesn't. As with most animal controls, there is a limit on what they will do or cover. At Pound Pets, there is no limit. Broken Bones, Surgery, Parvo, Heartworm, etc., if the animal has a chance the animal is given that chance. This is not a shelter but an animal control. 

Pound Pets Inc Rescue can always use more volunteers.
If you are interested in volunteering, the volunteer application is located here:

https://form.jotform.com/40307066949156

______________________________________________________________

We are always looking for licensed rescues to pull cats (including FIV+ cats) and dogs from the Granite City Animal Control in Madison County, Illinois. It's a very small animal control and strays keep coming in. There are no fees for a rescue to pull. If you can help us, please email the volunteers at poundpetsinc@gmail.com 

______________________________________________________________

Pound Pets Inc Animal Control Facebook Page:
https://www.facebook.com/poundpetsincorporated/

Pound Pets Inc Rescue Facebook Page:
https://www.facebook.com/poundpetsincrescue/

animal.description:
Meet our Dani!  This sweet girl was rescued locally.  Dani is an abuse case and has several injuries, including multiple upper and lower jaw fractures as well as a fracture to one of the bones in her left ear that assists with hearing.  Dani underwent weekly procedures for about 6 months and several surgeries and is now healed.  Unfortunately given the severity of the abuse, Dani will never appear normal but don't tell her that!  

Due to the abuse, Dani suffers from Microcephaly.  Dani also has severe separation anxiety/stress induced anxiety.  We have seen numerous specialists for this and Dani has been on multiple prescription medication but unfortunately none of these have assisted.  We believe that much of this is due to her brain injury.  

Despite all that she has been through, Dani is simply the happiest dog!  She does not know a stranger, 2 legged or 4 legged!  In typical lab fashion, she is an active girl but not overly active!   

Dani has earned her CGC, TDI, and CGCA titles.  

Dani cannot be crated.  She is about 90% housebroken but will have accidents once she is stressed and she will spin in her accidents.   

If you are interested in meeting Dani, please complete an application at our website, www.helporphanpuppies.org.  Please note our adoption requirements and feel free to contact us with any questions.  Thank you.

Please note:  All of our dogs are fostered locally a minimum of 2 weeks.  Adopting a dog that has been fostered locally is a very important consideration. Animals that are fostered locally in private homes allow the fosters to learn more about the dogs personality and allows for making the best match possible.  Also, animals that are transported into our area and placed directly often carry diseases, including parvo and distemper.  Animals can also become ill on transports to the northeast, as they are exposed to other animals in route.  If you have any questions regarding these diseases and the risks of not adopting locally, please contact your vet.  

Also consider any group that does not require a home visit.  If they are not conducting a home visit consider if they are vested in where their animals go.  As an organization, we invest a significant amount of time into all of our dogs, including crate training, house breaking, obedience training, and determining each dog's personality to consider making the best match possible.

Help Orphan Puppies is registered with the New York State Department of Agriculture and Markets. Our Rescue Registration Number is RR047.

animal.description:
This Fetch Fanatic will Surely Capture your Heart if Given the Chance! 

Lulu is such a wonderfully loving dog as soon as you enter her circle of trust! She prefers a hands off approach until she is comfortable – but would love to toss toys with you right off the bat! 

Love all the time! Lulu loves attention! She’s all about as much affection as she can receive! After slow and gentle introductions with people, her bold and expressive heart appears and she will shower you her smiling face, toys and snuggles on the couch.  She’ll share everything with people and everything but food with dogs. She’s a wonderful hangout buddy but needs mental and physical stimulation to keep her happy and settled in for the evening!

Impressive resume! Lulu is a smart gal. She already knows the commands look, touch, sit, down, shake, go to bed and is working on spin! She’s even learning the name of toys. She could certainly learn a lot more! Cars, baths, brushing…no problem! She’s housetrained and she’s so good, she doesn’t really need a crate, but handles the crate well.

Not perfect but close! Lulu needs slow introductions to everyone, especially dogs. She’s also best with dogs with similar energy levels as her. With people, she needs slow introductions and minimal touching until she trusts them. 

Lulu is happiest with lots of walks and/or runs especially if you live in an apartment. Her ideal family will give her regular outlet for exercise but she doesn’t need you to be super physical. She simply needs energy outlet and love.

animal.description:
ONE PERSON DOG, needs House and Yard.  NJ

4y 75lb Bruno Brunelli needs a solo person home.
Bruno is everything we love about the bully breeds: Very friendly, loose wiggly body and a waggy tail. He allowed counselor to pet him and rub his belly. He knows his commands of sit and stay. He allows all handling As per the client Bruno is house broken and friendly towards strangers. He has never bitten or scratched anyone to his knowledge. Bruno will chew up shoes if they are left out--so don't leave your shoes out as chew toys! Best in a home w/ no small children due to his energy, and because he is a big boy, w/ experienced bully adopters who know enough to be the alpha in the pack:)  He can be a bit territorial about his toys and food w/ other dogs so we think his ideal situation is a home w/ a yard and access to other doggies for playtime.  He definitely is not a city critter.  He loves puppies of all sizes and is a purrfect puppy nanny--Very tolerant of their play style.  

A volunteer writes: Bruno is a wiggly, playful, sweet bundle of joy! He pulls a little on leash, seems housebroken, sits for treats, and manages to immediately initiate a romance with any tennis ball he finds! I’m not sure I’ve ever met a dog who entertains himself as well!. He play bows with the ball, waltzes with it, rolls on his back with it, eventually chews it up, and then starts the whole cycle with the next one. Just watching him is enough to put a smile on anyone’s face, but he also loves interacting with people (and, so far, other dogs too!). He seems to be one of those dogs who sees a friend in every stranger (the kind of friend he can give kisses to and get belly rubs from!), but I can only imagine the extra-special-lovin’ he has reserved for his family. 

11/08/2016 BEHAVIOR AVERAGE Client came to drop off a dog that he stated was left in his apartment by his roommate. Intact, Owner Surrender Previously lived with: Adults
SAFER ASSESSMENT: 11/8/16 Look: 1. Dog’s eyes are averted. His ears are back, his tail is down, and he has a relaxed body posture. Dog allows head to be held loosely in Assessor’s cupped hands. Sensitivity: 1. Dog leans into the Assessor, eyes soft, soft and loose body, open mouth. Tag: 2. Dog is not fearful, but is unresponsive to the Assessor, and approaches the Assessor at the end of the game (need coaxing to approach.) He is focused on stimuli other than the Assessor. Squeeze 1 & 2: 1. Dog does not respond at all for three seconds. His eyes are averted and his ears are relaxed. Toy: 1. No interest. Summary: No concerns were seen on this assessment.
DOG-DOG INTERACTION ASSESSMENT: Summary PLAYGROUP: Bruno was surrendered as a stray so his past behavior around dogs is unknown. When off leash with dogs at the Care Center, Bruno engages in gentle play with male and female dogs. He is sexually motivated but able to continue to play when solicited. The Behavior Department recommends that Bruno be placed in a home with dogs that match his gentle play style and that a dog-dog interaction be conducted to ensure compatibility. MEDICAL BEHAVIOR: 11/04/16 During his initial medical examination, Bruno readily allowed all handling without issue. ENERGY LEVEL: Bruno displays a high activity level in the care center. RECOMMENDATIONS: Average (suitable for an adopter with an average amount of experience) Note: see potential challenges section below Potential challenges: _X_Destructive behavior: Bruno is a young, active, enthusiastic dog with lots of energy. He will need daily mental and physical exercise and stimulation to channel that energy appropriately. He is also reported to chew up shoes if they are left out, so this will need to be managed in his future home.

11/05/2016 GROUP BEHAVIOR EVALUATION When off leash with dogs at the Care Center, Bruno engages in gentle play with male and female dogs. He is sexually motivated but able to continue to play when solicited. The Behavior Department recommends that Bruno be placed in a home with dogs that match his gentle play style and that a dog-dog interaction be conducted to ensure compatibility. 11/5: Bruno displays loose and wiggly body language when greeting a novel female dog. He displays bouncy body language when the female solicits play. He explores the pen for a bit before attempting to mount again. 11/8-11/13: In a group of playful male and female dogs, Bruno displays soft body language when greeting the novel dogs. He is playful, engaging in and soliciting gentle play. He tolerates novice play styles.

Facebook: Zani's Furry Friends ZFF (weekly adoption event info posted here)

Please fill out an application at http://zanisfurryfriends.org and return to 
dogs@zanisfurryfriends.org 

Many of us (cats/dogs) will be on display on Sundays and sometimes on Saturdays--please ask by writing us at dogs@zanisfurryfriends.org and following us on FB. If you are seriously interested in adopting one of us in particular, please fill out an application by Friday so that we can be sure to be there. Otherwise we decide based on other variables. Please consider providing a home for more than one dog, especially if you are considering adopting a puppy. Dogs are pack animals and very much enjoy as well as need other dog company to learn to play, socialize and be good companion animals to people. The upside to this is that you won't feel as guilty leaving them alone and you get twice the love. Please come! And if you can't adopt, maybe you can foster or volunteer, and you can always donate!

Nala is such a pretty pittie!

This beautiful lady is Nala, a 4-year-old female Pit Bull Terrier mix. She has a smooth chocolate brown and white coat and is a good size dog weighing about 58 pounds.  Nala was pulled from our local animal shelter where she had been surrendered by her owner and down there for almost 3 months.  She had been adopted out one time down there but returned.

Nala is very friendly, playful and full of energy.  She loves to play with toys, especially tennis balls.  She would be a great dog to take on long walks, hiking or jogging cause she has a lot of stamina.

Nala plays well with other dogs and should be fine with children ages 12 and up. She may have too much energy for an apartment.  She will require a fenced in yard and a home visit will be done to verify.  We have started on her crate training. Nala is up to date on her vet care, spayed, heartworm negative and is microchipped.  She is on heartworm and flea/tick prevention.

Nala is a very loving dog that will make a great companion for a very lucky owner!

Our adoption fee is $75. Read more information on our adoption process at www.humanesocietyofwa.org/howtoadopt.html. Then, if you feel your home might be the right forever home and you would like to adopt a dog, submit an online adoption application. The online applications may not work on mobile devices. animal.description:
Hi my name is Tate, but you can call me Tater or Tato, like my foster family does. I was born in September of 2016 under a shed in a rural area outside of Atlanta and boy am I lucky that a rescue group found me and my siblings and took us in.

My Mom was a Border Collie mix and I am not sure about Dad but he was obviously one handsome dude. I am a medium size dog and weigh about 40lbs.  I am house trained and crate trained and I’m a super smart boy. My foster mom says I’m the smartest dog she’s ever had but I have a lot of anxiety and am very nervous in new situations and with new people. Once I feel comfortable though I am just a big goofball and my favorite thing to do is snuggle. I need a home that will understand that I do not like to do the things that most dogs do, like go for walks. I prefer to stay inside where I feel safe so I will  need someone to be patient with me and give me time to get acclimated.  I will do best in a home without small children or other pets and with a fenced yard.

I am looking for my forever family. Wanna meet me? Just send an email to info@barkvilledogrescue.org or submit an application for me at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

"I think everything is fun, interesting and meant for play, especially you. Anything you do, I'll want to do too. With my own brand of surprises, life with me will keep you constantly on your toes, and the fun is guaranteed. (Socially motivated)"

Prepare for wiggles and a dog that thinks he's part Kangaroo! Po is very nervous of new people, especially strange men, and strange dogs. We are looking for a relaxed household with experience (or someone willing to attend training classes) to help this boy overcome his past and social issues. Once he opens up to new people he is a total charmer, however and he is sure to be the goofball of the family. He would not do well in a family with children under 13 years old, or in a home with other dogs. This is merely so we can set him up for success. He had a rough start at the beginning of his short life: an island dog with no home, and then a lack of socialization made him unsure of his world. He's learning that people can be good, but he's got a ways to go. Once you are his person he wants to protect you, and he is as happy as can be. If you think you could be the knight in shining armor that Po is looking for, please give us a call to set up an appointment to meet this sweet boy. You can also email our trainer at jessica.barlow@aacspca.org for more info about him.

animal.description:
This guy loves to be outside so a person w/ a lot of outdoor time and then snuggly time is Zazu's ideal home.  But he is for EXPERIENCED adopters only, a solo person in the home, no guests, no children and not in a City environment.

8y 38lb Zazu fka Zebracake is a good looking gent, reasonably well groomed and dressed in a lush dark chocolate and black coat. His amber eyes light up his face. His muzzle is very slightly grey, and his mouth opens often into a lovely smile. Zazu is a little shy in his kennel, but gets leashed fairly rapidly. He is a very good walker, marks a little his territory, and eyes the pigeons as well as the squirrels in the park. Well, he is just doing his job, as he is part of the herding group of dogs. Zazu does not mind being stared at by me and the camera. He will sit on command, and is not at all interested in my treats that I thought were quite tasty. He seems to like my caresses all over his body. He is a really very gentle and well-mannered pooch. As we were early visitors at a nearby park, we did not meet many dogs, and those we encountered did not elicit much attention from Zazu.  He is an easy going character, friendly, a little shy–at least inside our walls–and a lovely Collie/Retriever mix who is sure to attract connoisseurs of the breeds. 

Facebook: Zani's Furry Friends ZFF (weekly adoption event info posted here)
Instagram: zanisfurryfriends 
Twitter: zanisff 

Please fill out an application in copy/paste format into the body of the email at http://zanisfurryfriends.org and return to dogs@zanisfurryfriends.org 

Many of us (cats/dogs) will be on display on Sundays and sometimes on Saturdays--please ask by writing us at dogs@zanisfurryfriends.org and following us on FB. If you are seriously interested in adopting one of us in particular, please fill out an application by Friday so that we can be sure to be there. Otherwise we decide based on other variables. Usually we are in our foster homes or in boarding so this is a bit more stressful and a slightly artificial environment but we do want to be seen and find our furever homes too.

Please consider providing a home for more than one dog, especially if you are considering adopting a puppy. Dogs are pack animals and very much enjoy as well as need other dog company to learn to play, socialize and be good companion animals to people. The upside to this is that you won't feel as guilty leaving them alone and you get twice the love. Please come! And if you can't adopt, maybe you can foster or volunteer, and you can always donate!

animal.description:
Cesaer, a Black Lab with the English look to him!  A Big grown up puppy, in spirit and demeanor.  Found walking across 5 lanes of traffic, a very busy intersection. with 2 people who didn't care.  No leash and I flipped around thru a gas station, a red light and pulled into a shopping center asking if he was their dog...NO...fine...I looped him.  Happy Boy!  My truck was empty of stuff...back doors open...he didn't want any of it!  No jumping up and I had my work clothes on...don't get me dirty...dog!  I shut all the doors and went for my passenger front seat - oh boy - he was ready for the Ride!!!  Jumped right in!

Somebody's dog...neutered, clean, happy boy, Lost with a collar and no tags, drove him straight to the vet to scan for a microchip...nothing!

So I posted Found on websites, put up fliers, nothing...no Lost signs either...oh well.

He needs a family who cares!  He's pretty good on leash, wants back in the house!  But he jumps on the door - and out he goes...probably why he was Lost!.

He loves the fenced in back yard and is happy to come when called.  He's young, happy and will stay that way here.  Great in his crate, tail waggles at everyone he meets, gets really excited at children playing in neighborhood...speaks Spanish, I'm sure...  Playing great with Lexi (listed separately).  He was HW positive, and now he's negative!

for more Info - call Julie 770-329-4742 or email for application:  jachambers4806@yahoo.com

Pet Adoptions - Sat. 2-6 pm - call ahead for attendance and location.

animal.description:
Meet Carson Dukes. His eyes (one blue, one brown) are unique and strikingly gorgeous, one myth even says that dogs with two different color eyes can view heaven and earth at the same time.

Carson is an adult Border Collie mix who has been with us since he was just a pup. Like some of our others he can be a bit shy and timid around new people so he would benefit from an adopter who is willing to spend some time with him at our kennel. Once he figures out who will be his friend he is very loving. Oh, and he is a bit of an escape artist, six feet or chain link does not hold a challenge for him. He never leaves us; he just doesnt like to be fenced. Carson would be a great indoor companion with supervised outdoor exercise. 

Carson recently spent some time in a foster home. He adjusted well to being a house dog, is crate trained, and almost housebroken. He got along with the other dogs, really enjoyed stretching his long legs running and playing in the yard, and was happily contained with the 8ft privacy fence. His foster family describes him as, "lovable, sweet, playful, and quirky in the most endearing way." 

Carson's adoption fee includes neuter, microchip, current vaccinations, and up to date heartworm/flea/tick prevention.

Interested in fostering or adopting? Complete our online application at dollygoodpuppy.org

animal.description:
Ruben & Tyler are a BONDED pair and being returned to our rescue after 4 years and need an foster home ASAP!!

Estimated date of birth: 8/15
Ruben has an interesting story that proves he is a true survivor in the harshest of environments.  Back in April 2016, some very kind citizens in Stockton noticed 3 little dogs running around the area where the City Food Bank is located.  Not a very safe area for dogs to be wandering off leash.  These dogs were very skiddish.  They were able to catch Shirley, then a few weeks later her brother Tyler, but little Ruben went MIA, but would show up now and again, all by himself, alone and scared.  The citizens never gave up on him and continued to try to get him to safety.  Well, they finally succeeded.  He is a shy boy, but when he is in a safe stable environment, he comes out of his shell and loves to be a lap doggy.  He also likes to snuggle in bed with you, but is crate trained as well.  Little man Ruben deserves a wonderful home where he will be cherished and kept warm and safe. He is neutered, microchipped and current on his vaccines. If you'd like to meet Ruben,  please contact EOE at eoerescue@yahoo.com, or 209-815-5186

animal.description:
Alexander is a 4 year old handsome blue-eyed boy! He is playful and sweet with his foster furry and human siblings. 

He would love a family with no small children, but will need a patient, experienced owner that is willing to love him through some initial possible marking, resource guarding and stubbornness.  He is crate trained and potty trained.  He eats and sleeps in his crate!  He is improving with his collar sensitivity but new owners will need to work with him as well.  

**He NEEDS AN EXPERIENCED OWNER! We will not accept applications for first time owners!**

If you are interested in pursuing an adoption and you live in Texas , please complete the application (links provided below). The process includes a vet check, calling references and doing a home visit. 

http://www.texassleddogrescue.org/web_documents/tsdr_application.pdf
or
https://www.formstack.com/forms/?1632205-WX2Zb144ZP

Please note the following:
We rarely do out of state adoptions.  (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience and will require same adoption process.)
Children in the home or that visit often must be at least 6 years of age. (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience.)
Adoption donation is due at the time of adoption.  Puppies under 1 year are $300. Dogs 1 year to 7 years are $200 and dogs over 7 years are $150.  As this is a donation, it will be non-returnable if dog is returned to rescue.
Dogs are not placed on a "first come, first serve" basis but rather the best home for the dog. 
All dogs placed by TSDR will be:
spayed/neutered
vaccinated for distemper/parvo, rabies, and bordetella
heartworm tested and treated if needed
microchipped
other vetting as deemed needed
New owners will receive copies of all available vet information and must agree to keep them current on all of the above.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: small animals like rabbits, squirrels, hamsters due to prey drive
